conjecture(pnt): the primes thin out like x over log x

Gauss and Legendre, from tables of primes, conjecture that the number of primes
below x is asymptotic to x divided by the natural logarithm of x.

Status: math.conjectured
---
proof(chebyshev): the count is of the right order

Chebyshev proves that the prime count is bounded above and below by constant
multiples of x over log x, but cannot pin the constant to one.

Status: math.proved-informal
---
proof(zeta-nonvanishing): the zeta function has no zero on the line Re(s) = 1

The Riemann zeta function does not vanish on the edge of the critical strip. This
analytic fact is exactly what an asymptotic count needs.

Status: math.proved-informal
---
proof(hadamard): an analytic proof via the zeta function

Hadamard derives the asymptotic law from the non-vanishing of zeta on the line,
using complex analysis.

Status: math.proved-informal
Depends-On: zeta-nonvanishing
Closes: conjecture:pnt
---
proof(de-la-vallee-poussin): an independent analytic proof the same year

De la Vallee Poussin proves the theorem independently, also from the zeta
non-vanishing, with sharper error terms.

Status: math.proved-informal
Depends-On: zeta-nonvanishing
Closes: conjecture:pnt
---
proof(erdos-selberg): an elementary proof with no complex analysis

Erdos and Selberg prove the theorem by real-variable methods alone, resting on
none of the zeta machinery.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:pnt
Cites: Erdos and Selberg, 1949
---
formalize(pnt): a kernel-checked proof in Isabelle

Avigad and collaborators formalise the elementary proof in Isabelle, so the
asymptotic law is checked by the kernel.

Formal-Statement: isabelle:PNT.prime_number_theorem
Status: math.machine-checked
Verified-By: Isabelle
Closes: conjecture:pnt
Cites: Avigad et al. 2007
---
conjecture(rh): every non-trivial zero of zeta lies on the critical line

The Riemann hypothesis: all non-trivial zeros of the zeta function have real part
one half. Still open.

Status: math.conjectured
---
proof(pnt-error-rh): on the Riemann hypothesis, a near-optimal error term

If the Riemann hypothesis holds, the difference between the prime count and the
logarithmic integral is bounded by the square root of x times log x. The argument
is complete, but it rests on an open conjecture.

Status: math.proved-informal
Depends-On: pnt
Assumes: rh

